@NODE "Installation"
@PREV "Requirements"
@NEXT "Introduction"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Installation
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}

  If you want Ned to be running every time you boot up, copy the Ned
  executable and its icon to SYS:WBStartup, or copy it wherever you
  like and run it from your User-Startup.

  Althoug Ned doesn't need a prefs file to operate and is functional right
  out of the box, you can configure it for greater control on how it
  should react on some windows. To do this you create a prefs file for the
  program and copy it to ENV: for the default configuration. This path can
  be changed, but if you choose to use ENV: don't forget to copy the prefs
  file to ENVARC: for permanent use.  Creating the prefs file and how to
  alter the path will be discussed later.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Introduction"
@PREV "Installation"
@NEXT "Features"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Introduction
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}

  Ned is a handy AmigaOS commodity that allows you to close the active
  window by pressing the ESCAPE key.

  Furthermore, it can send intuition events to the active windows or execute
  AmigaOS executable files on a press of the ESCAPE key.

  There are a few problems that a program like Ned should be able to solve:

  - Some programs enter their iconify modes when the user clicks on their
    windows' CLOSE gadgets. Whether this behaviour is correct or not is
    out the score of this manual, but by using Ned you can send these
    kinds of windows user configurable intuition events like @{B}RAMIGA Q@{UB}
    to ask them to quit instead of becomming iconified.

  - Contrary to the above, there are situations when you want a program
    to enter its iconify mode on the press of ESCAPE key. If the program
    has an ICONIFY menu item, you can configure Ned to send it that event.
    If not, maybe the program has an AREXX port, and you can configure Ned
    to execute an AREXX script that asks the program to iconify its window.

  - There are situations when you want a program's window to actually
    receive the ESCAPE events. As an example, some Bulletin Board Systems
    require that the user presses the ESCAPE key twice to enter the system.
    You can configure Ned to skip the window of the communication program
    that you use to connect to these systems and to send the coming ESCAPE
    events back to them.

  - Because the events that Ned can send to your programs' windows are
    configurable, you can create a single interface for quitting programs,
    regardless of the language that they use. You can cofigure Ned to
    send your Swedish Amiga program a @{B}RAMIGA A@{UB} that is often used for
    quitting Swedish programs.

  Possible scenarios when Ned can help you solve the above problems
  have been disccused in the @{"Example prefs file" LINK "Example prefs file"} chapter of this manual.

  Once you start using Ned, you'll wonder how you ever used your computer
  without having access to a single interface to quit applications.

  Ned gives life to the, often not used, ESCAPE key on your keyboard and
  allows you to use one interface to quit programs.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Features"
@PREV "Introduction"
@NEXT "Usage"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Features
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}


  - Ned is an AmigaOS commodity.

  - It is small, fast and system friendly.

  - It can click on the CLOSE gadget of the active window on pressing the
    ESCAPE key.

  - It can send a user configurable intuition event to a window on
    pressing the ESCAPE key.

  - Ned can execute an AmigaOS executables on pressing the ESCAPE key over
    the active window.

  - It can be configured to skip some windows by sending the ESCAPE events
    back to them.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage"
@PREV "Features"
@NEXT "Configuration"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Usage
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}


  Upon startup, Ned tries to read a prefs file that contains information
  about how it should handle some windows. If a prefs file is not available,
  the default options will be used for all windows.

  When running, Ned sits in the background waiting for the user to press the
  ESCAPE key. Upon  receiving that, Ned tries to close the active window buy
  clicking on its CLOSE window gadget if one is available or by sending it
  a @{B}RAMIGA Q@{UB} intuition event if the window has an attached MenuStrip. If
  neither of these are available, Ned simply sends the ESCAPE event back to
  the window.

  You can start Ned from a Shell or Workbench. The program accepts the
  following arguments or tooltypes:

    @{B}BeCurious:@{UB} (Optional) By default, Ned sends the incoming ESCAPE events
               back to windows that do not carry title bars. The reason for
               this behavior is that Ned only uses the information in the
               title bar of windows for its configuration.

               Although quite uncommon, some programs' windows have attached
               MenuStrips even if they do not carry title bars.

               Even if it is not recommended, you can configure Ned to send
               its default intuition event (@{B}RAMIGA Q@{UB}) to these kinds of
               window.

               @{B}BeCurious=YES@{UB}    activates the curious mode of the program.
               @{B}BeCurious=NO@{UB}     does nothing (default option).

               Please use the default mode of the program if you do not
               understand what all this means. ;-)

    @{B}Prefs:@{UB}     (Optional) By default, Ned looks for the file ENV:Ned.prefs upon
               startup.  You can use the 'prefs' argument if you locate Ned's
               prefs file somewhere else.

               For example:

               @{B}Prefs=Ned.prefs@{UB} tells Ned to use the prefs file 'Ned.prefs'
               that is located in the same directory as the program itself.

               @{B}Prefs=S:Ned_Lisa.prefs@{UB} tells Ned to use the prefs file
               'Ned_Lisa.prefs' located in the directory S:


  When run from a shell or somewhere in your startup make sure to
  use @{B}run >nil: Ned@{UB} if you want to be able to close the console
  window.

  Ned doesn't allow you to launch multiple copies of itself.

  To quit Ned, you should send a break to Ned's main task with tools
  like Scout, XOper or ARTM.  This is the same as pressing @{B}CTRL-C@{UB} or
  using "Break `Status COM=<path>Ned` C" in the Shell if you start the
  program from a Shell window.

  Being an AmigaOS commodity, you can Activate, Deactivate or Quit Ned
  by using AmigaOS Commodities Exchange program.


@ENDNODE


@NODE "Configuration"
@PREV "Usage"
@NEXT "Example prefs file"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Configuration
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}


  ENV:Ned.prefs is an ordinary ASCII file that you can create with
  your favorite text editor.

  Empty lines and lines that begin with a semicolon (;) or a space ( )
  are considered comment lines and will be ignored.

  If Ned finds an error in its prefs file, it will gently inform you about
  what and where in the prefs file the faulty information is located and quit.

  The ENV:Ned.prefs file consists of a number of objects.  An object
  is a group of lines that describes what window is affected and how
  it is affected.  Each object must be separated with a pound sign (#).

  Use space characters only when they are needed, for example as part
  of a window title.

  To define an object, the title of a window has to be given. As Ned supports
  AmigaDOS wildcarding, '#?' would replace any number of any characters.

    @{B}Title=@{UB}The window's title#?


  For each defined object, one of 3 types of actions can be defined.

    @{B}InsertEvent=@{UB}The event that Ned should send to the window

      This can be anything from sending the window a single character
      like "c" or a complex event like "RAMIGA Q"

    @{B}Execute=@{UB}The program that Ned should execute

      Ned executes the executable AmigaDOS program upon receiving the ESCAPE
      key on the active window.

    @{B}Skip=@{UB}YES|NO

      Ned SKIPS this window.

  For example:

  Title=Program A#?
  InsertEvent=control c
  #

  tells Ned to send the window whose title begins with the words @{B}Program A@{UB}
  the @{B}CTRL C@{UB} intuition event upon receiving the ESCAPE key.

  More examples are available in the @{"Example prefs file" LINK "Example prefs file"} section of this manual.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Example prefs file"
@PREV "Configuration"
@NEXT "FAQ"
@TOC "Main"


  @{B}Example prefs file
  @{U}                                                                             @{UU}@{UB}


  ; Begin your comment lines with a ';'
  ; End each object with a '#'
  ;
  ; A window title and one of the supported actions have to be defined for
  ; each object.
  ;
  ; --- Window title
  ; Title=Window's title (wildcarding is accepted)
  ;
  ; --- Supported actions in the current version
  ; InsertEvent=The event Ned should send to the window
  ; Execute=The program Ned should execute
  ; Skip=YES|NO

  ; Program A closes its window upon receiving "Ctrl C".
  Title=Program A#?
  InsertEvent=control c
  #

  ; Iconify the window of Program B instead of quitting it by sending it
  ; an INONIFY AREXX command upon receiving the ESCAPE key.
  Title=Program B
  Execute=rx "address PROGRAMB.1; 'ICONIFY'"
  #

  ; Program C closes its window upon receiving the single character 'c'.
  Title=Program C
  InsertEvent=c
  #

  ; Program D closes its window upos receiving the 'F2' function key.
  Title=Program D
  InsertEvent=F2
  #

  ; Program E becomes iconified when the user clicks on its CLOSE window
  ; gadget.
  ; It quits when the user chooses the menu item "QUIT Q" so we configure
  ; Ned to to send this window "RAMIGA Q" on pressing the ESCAPE key.
  Title=Program E#?
  InsertEvent=RAmiga q
  #

  ; The Swedish "Program F" becomes iconified when user clicks on its CLOSE
  ; window gadget.
  ; It quits when the user chooses the menu item "AVSLUTA A" (AVSLUTA stands
  ; for QUIT in Swedish) so we configure Ned to to send this window "RAMIGA A"
  ; on pressing the ESCAPE key.
  Title=Program F#?
  InsertEvent=RAmiga q
  #

  ; The BBS system requires the user to press the ESCAPE key twice to enter
  ; the system. To do this we configure Ned to skip the window of the terminal
  ; program that is used for calling the BBS.
  Title=My simple terminal program
  Skip=YES
  #

@ENDNODE

